INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("127", "1", "2013-12-22 14:29:24", "2013-12-22 14:29:24", "From a long weekend getaway to a month-long cross-country adventure, travelers who use wheelchairs and mobility scooters have choices when it comes to vacation transportation. Just think a moment before your make your next vacation transportation reservation…\r\n\r\nIf you’re goal is to get where you’re going as fast as possible, book a flight on an airline. Be sure to request a plane with double-wide aisles, fully handicap-accessible bathrooms, and caring, concerned personnel. (If you find one, please let us all know!) Passenger trains like AmTrak have limited accessible accommodations, so make your reservations well in advance. Got ocean? Cruise ships also have accessible staterooms. Or—\r\n\r\nPlan a leisurely trip using short-term rental transportation created for your comfort, convenience, and personal pleasure!\r\n\r\nFrom a long weekend getaway to a month-long cross-country adventure, travelers who use wheelchairs and mobility scooters have choices when it comes to vacation transportation. Just think a moment before your make your next vacation transportation reservation…\r\n\r\nIf you’re goal is to get where you’re going as fast as possible, book a flight on an airline. Be sure to request a plane with double-wide aisles, fully handicap-accessible bathrooms, and caring, concerned personnel. (If you find one, please let us all know!) Passenger trains like AmTrak have limited accessible accommodations, so make your reservations well in advance. Got ocean? Cruise ships also have accessible staterooms. Or—\r\n\r\nPlan a leisurely trip using short-term rental transportation created for your comfort, convenience, and personal pleasure!\r\n<h2>Where To Find Handicap Vans For Rent</h2>\r\nMost local and online wheelchair van dealers have a rental component. If you live near a city with one or more handicap van dealerships, call for information. Wheelchair van conversions are innovatively modified for the transportation needs of individuals with mobility issues, and every conversion feature is intended to make your travel life substantially easier. Even when you fly to your destination, you might want to consider renting a modified van at that location for stress-free sightseeing.\r\n\r\nOnline van dealerships often have satellite dealerships in your area that can provide you with a rental vehicle. Even if you live in a remote area, it’s possible to have a rental van delivered to your front door, though you’ll typically be charged a nominal fee for delivery and pick-up. Like all rentals, fees and terms vary, so do a little research first.\r\n<h2>What to Look For in a Wheelchair Accessible Van</h2>\r\nYour particular requirements will determine the best adapted van choice for your vacation. Accessible vans can be configured for up to two wheelchair passengers and, if you’re a wheelchair user capable of 1) transferring from your wheelchair into the driver’s seat and 2) driving without the use of hand controls, you can take the wheel! Some rentals may also include hand controls in the package. Just ask.\r\n\r\nIt’s in your best interest to work with a mobility consultant at the rental company. Your first decision will be the access and exit point on the van—do you need a side entry or rear entry wheelchair van conversion?\r\n\r\nA side entry handicap van works best for most situations, especially when you want to drive and your travel partners include another wheelchair user and one or two able-bodied passengers. If you don’t plan to drive, and you’ll be the only passenger in a wheelchair, the side entry van is ideal, with lots of cabin space to maneuver, and you can travel sitting in your wheelchair or transfer to special seating, leaving plenty of room for luggage and other cargo. The main drawback with a rear entry van is that wheelchair passengers must back out of the vehicle, which isn’t necessary with the side entry, but it’s sometimes easier to find parking for rear-entry wheelchair vans, so inquire about parking considerations for both styles.\r\n\r\nAn accessible van with “kneeling” capability, though not necessary, might be considered in cases where the driver needs wheelchair access or the wheelchair passenger(s) lack upper-body strength. A kneeling system reduces the incline of the deployed ramp, making it easier to enter and exit. If you’re traveling with able-bodied companions or a caretaker, navigating a ramp without a kneeling system shouldn’t be a problem.\r\n\r\nAlso look for safe, reliable wheelchair docking systems and tie-downs, ample cabin space (which modified minivans and full-size vans typically have), sufficient seating for your travel partners, low mileage, and powered ramp deployment with manual back-up. Your vacation—your choice.\r\n<h2>How Adapted Van Rental Typically Works</h2>\r\nMost handicap van dealerships with a rental component offer short-term (long weekend, weekly) or longer-term (monthly, as well as extended periods for situations like temporary, post-op recovery when mobility is impaired.) Some rental companies have one-day or one-week minimums, so be sure to ask.\r\n\r\nA mobility consultant should work with you to identify the best rental van for your trip. When you pick up the vehicle, or it’s delivered to your driveway, a mobility professional should provide complete instructions on how to operate your wheelchair van rental, which is so easy to use, you’ll be on the road in no time!\r\n\r\nExpect the daily rental price to be higher than standard auto rentals. After all, you’re getting luxurious accommodations designed especially for the wheelchair traveler. Most adapted van rental companies offer daily, weekly, monthly, and extended rates, with “extra day” rates, and the rates often include a maximum daily mileage with a reduced daily charge for additional travel days.\r\n<h2>What to Ask Before You Rent</h2>\r\nMost of the following information should appear on the rental contract and web site of a reputable handicap accessible van dealership under their Rental information, and these are important things to think about as you begin the process:\r\n<h3>Rental Requirements</h3>\r\nAll drivers of accessible rentals must meet an age requirement that may vary by company, and typically must have a valid driver’s license and proof of insurance as well as vehicle renter’s insurance (full coverage), obtained personally or through the rental company. Find out what the company offers. The driver also needs a clean driver history, and you’ll need a credit card (American Express, Visa, MasterCard, or another card accepted by the rental company.)\r\n<h3>Service Animals</h3>\r\nService animals are generally permitted, and you should let the rental company know ahead of time that you’ll be traveling with a four-legged, service companion. Expect to pay a one-time cleaning fee if necessary. A cleaning fee will also be in effect for non-service animals that join you. The fee will depend on the interior condition of the van when you return.\r\n<h3>Pre-Rental Condition</h3>\r\nMake sure you and the rental agent record any existing dents, dings, and interior issues before you accept the van and drive away, so you don’t have to pay for damage you don’t cause. A copy of that information should be included in the paperwork you take (and take care of) on the trip. That said, your rental van should be presented to you in great condition everywhere—interior, exterior, and under the hood.\r\n<h3>Cancellation Policy</h3>\r\nIn most cases, your rental reservation can be canceled at any time with no penalty. In turn, the rental company would tremendously appreciate your cancellation notice as soon as possible in order to make your reserved van available to another individual or family.\r\n<h3>MPG</h3>\r\nFind out how many miles to the gallon the van gets, and how many gallons the tank holds, so you can plan your stops and budget in advance for gas.\r\n<h3>Vehicle/Conversion Malfunction</h3>\r\nExpect nothing. Be ready for anything. You should be prepared for any eventuality on the road, though a low-mileage van and a well-designed, well- crafted conversion should be virtually trouble- and worry-free. A reputable rental company will have a nationwide service and repair network and 24-hour conversion help line, so if something goes wrong with the vehicle itself or the conversion (ramp, docking system, etc.), you’ll simply make a phone call to find and get the help you need.\r\n<h3>Returning the Van</h3>\r\nAgain, rental policies vary, but most are the same as standard rental car policies. The gas tank must be filled to the level at pick-up or delivery. Easy enough to accomplish when you stop at a gas station with a car wash (see Cleaning Fee below)—otherwise expect to pay for the refill plus a possible service fee. Also, check for late charges that may apply if the van isn’t returned by the agreed-upon time.\r\n<h3>Cleaning Fee</h3>\r\nA cleaning fee (in the range of $100) may or may not be charged upon your return, depending on whether the van needs more than a routine cleaning (exterior wash, dusting, vacuuming). You might want stop by a car wash in the rental vehicle before you return it to clean it out, make it look as good as the day you began your journey, and avoid a cleaning fee.\r\n<h3>Smoking</h3>\r\nAs a rule, smoking is not permitted in rented handicap vans, and the companies have the ability to detect the odor of cigarette or cigar smoke. You will be charged, so violating the rule is ill-advised.\r\n<h3>Multiple Drivers</h3>\r\nTypically, multiple drivers are permitted as long as they’re listed on the rental contract, have a valid driver’s license, and are covered under a primary renter’s insurance policy.\r\n<h3>Necessary Papers</h3>\r\nBefore you hit the road for parts known and unknown, double-check all the paperwork you have onboard (contract, essential phone numbers, vehicle handbook, etc.), so you’re 100% adventure-ready!\r\n<h3>Where Can I Go?</h3>\r\nYou can’t go to the moon or overseas, and you typically can’t take a rental van out of the US, but all other destinations are awaiting your arrival. It’s time to ramp up your vacation plans!\r\n<h2>About the author</h2>\r\nSusan Hawkins is a writer for AMSVans.com, which rents and sells wheelchair vans and all types of adapted vehicles nationwide with a guaranteed low price on all newly converted AMS-brand wheelchair van models. We sell and convert wheelchair-accessible vans at prices often thousands of dollars lower than the competition. AMSvans.com also accepts trades buys used wheelchair vans at competitive prices. Find adaptive mobility equipment solutions as well as more than 150 handicap vans for sale online at <a href=\"http://www.amsvans.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.amsvans.com</a>.", "Guest Journal: “How To Rent a Wheelchair Van for Your Next Vacation” by Susan Hawkins of AMS Vans", "", "publish", "open", "open", "", "renting-a-wheelchair", "", "", "2013-12-22 14:29:24", "2013-12-22 14:29:24", "", "0", "http://abilitytripwp/?p=127", "0", "post", "", "0");
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES("128", "1", "2013-12-22 14:29:24", "2013-12-22 14:29:24", "From a long weekend getaway to a month-long cross-country adventure, travelers who use wheelchairs and mobility scooters have choices when it comes to vacation transportation. Just think a moment before your make your next vacation transportation reservation…\r\n\r\nIf you’re goal is to get where you’re going as fast as possible, book a flight on an airline. Be sure to request a plane with double-wide aisles, fully handicap-accessible bathrooms, and caring, concerned personnel. (If you find one, please let us all know!) Passenger trains like AmTrak have limited accessible accommodations, so make your reservations well in advance. Got ocean? Cruise ships also have accessible staterooms. Or—\r\n\r\nPlan a leisurely trip using short-term rental transportation created for your comfort, convenience, and personal pleasure!\r\n\r\nFrom a long weekend getaway to a month-long cross-country adventure, travelers who use wheelchairs and mobility scooters have choices when it comes to vacation transportation. Just think a moment before your make your next vacation transportation reservation…\r\n\r\nIf you’re goal is to get where you’re going as fast as possible, book a flight on an airline. Be sure to request a plane with double-wide aisles, fully handicap-accessible bathrooms, and caring, concerned personnel. (If you find one, please let us all know!) Passenger trains like AmTrak have limited accessible accommodations, so make your reservations well in advance. Got ocean? Cruise ships also have accessible staterooms. Or—\r\n\r\nPlan a leisurely trip using short-term rental transportation created for your comfort, convenience, and personal pleasure!\r\n<h2>Where To Find Handicap Vans For Rent</h2>\r\nMost local and online wheelchair van dealers have a rental component. If you live near a city with one or more handicap van dealerships, call for information. Wheelchair van conversions are innovatively modified for the transportation needs of individuals with mobility issues, and every conversion feature is intended to make your travel life substantially easier. Even when you fly to your destination, you might want to consider renting a modified van at that location for stress-free sightseeing.\r\n\r\nOnline van dealerships often have satellite dealerships in your area that can provide you with a rental vehicle. Even if you live in a remote area, it’s possible to have a rental van delivered to your front door, though you’ll typically be charged a nominal fee for delivery and pick-up. Like all rentals, fees and terms vary, so do a little research first.\r\n<h2>What to Look For in a Wheelchair Accessible Van</h2>\r\nYour particular requirements will determine the best adapted van choice for your vacation. Accessible vans can be configured for up to two wheelchair passengers and, if you’re a wheelchair user capable of 1) transferring from your wheelchair into the driver’s seat and 2) driving without the use of hand controls, you can take the wheel! Some rentals may also include hand controls in the package. Just ask.\r\n\r\nIt’s in your best interest to work with a mobility consultant at the rental company. Your first decision will be the access and exit point on the van—do you need a side entry or rear entry wheelchair van conversion?\r\n\r\nA side entry handicap van works best for most situations, especially when you want to drive and your travel partners include another wheelchair user and one or two able-bodied passengers. If you don’t plan to drive, and you’ll be the only passenger in a wheelchair, the side entry van is ideal, with lots of cabin space to maneuver, and you can travel sitting in your wheelchair or transfer to special seating, leaving plenty of room for luggage and other cargo. The main drawback with a rear entry van is that wheelchair passengers must back out of the vehicle, which isn’t necessary with the side entry, but it’s sometimes easier to find parking for rear-entry wheelchair vans, so inquire about parking considerations for both styles.\r\n\r\nAn accessible van with “kneeling” capability, though not necessary, might be considered in cases where the driver needs wheelchair access or the wheelchair passenger(s) lack upper-body strength. A kneeling system reduces the incline of the deployed ramp, making it easier to enter and exit. If you’re traveling with able-bodied companions or a caretaker, navigating a ramp without a kneeling system shouldn’t be a problem.\r\n\r\nAlso look for safe, reliable wheelchair docking systems and tie-downs, ample cabin space (which modified minivans and full-size vans typically have), sufficient seating for your travel partners, low mileage, and powered ramp deployment with manual back-up. Your vacation—your choice.\r\n<h2>How Adapted Van Rental Typically Works</h2>\r\nMost handicap van dealerships with a rental component offer short-term (long weekend, weekly) or longer-term (monthly, as well as extended periods for situations like temporary, post-op recovery when mobility is impaired.) Some rental companies have one-day or one-week minimums, so be sure to ask.\r\n\r\nA mobility consultant should work with you to identify the best rental van for your trip. When you pick up the vehicle, or it’s delivered to your driveway, a mobility professional should provide complete instructions on how to operate your wheelchair van rental, which is so easy to use, you’ll be on the road in no time!\r\n\r\nExpect the daily rental price to be higher than standard auto rentals. After all, you’re getting luxurious accommodations designed especially for the wheelchair traveler. Most adapted van rental companies offer daily, weekly, monthly, and extended rates, with “extra day” rates, and the rates often include a maximum daily mileage with a reduced daily charge for additional travel days.\r\n<h2>What to Ask Before You Rent</h2>\r\nMost of the following information should appear on the rental contract and web site of a reputable handicap accessible van dealership under their Rental information, and these are important things to think about as you begin the process:\r\n<h3>Rental Requirements</h3>\r\nAll drivers of accessible rentals must meet an age requirement that may vary by company, and typically must have a valid driver’s license and proof of insurance as well as vehicle renter’s insurance (full coverage), obtained personally or through the rental company. Find out what the company offers. The driver also needs a clean driver history, and you’ll need a credit card (American Express, Visa, MasterCard, or another card accepted by the rental company.)\r\n<h3>Service Animals</h3>\r\nService animals are generally permitted, and you should let the rental company know ahead of time that you’ll be traveling with a four-legged, service companion. Expect to pay a one-time cleaning fee if necessary. A cleaning fee will also be in effect for non-service animals that join you. The fee will depend on the interior condition of the van when you return.\r\n<h3>Pre-Rental Condition</h3>\r\nMake sure you and the rental agent record any existing dents, dings, and interior issues before you accept the van and drive away, so you don’t have to pay for damage you don’t cause. A copy of that information should be included in the paperwork you take (and take care of) on the trip. That said, your rental van should be presented to you in great condition everywhere—interior, exterior, and under the hood.\r\n<h3>Cancellation Policy</h3>\r\nIn most cases, your rental reservation can be canceled at any time with no penalty. In turn, the rental company would tremendously appreciate your cancellation notice as soon as possible in order to make your reserved van available to another individual or family.\r\n<h3>MPG</h3>\r\nFind out how many miles to the gallon the van gets, and how many gallons the tank holds, so you can plan your stops and budget in advance for gas.\r\n<h3>Vehicle/Conversion Malfunction</h3>\r\nExpect nothing. Be ready for anything. You should be prepared for any eventuality on the road, though a low-mileage van and a well-designed, well- crafted conversion should be virtually trouble- and worry-free. A reputable rental company will have a nationwide service and repair network and 24-hour conversion help line, so if something goes wrong with the vehicle itself or the conversion (ramp, docking system, etc.), you’ll simply make a phone call to find and get the help you need.\r\n<h3>Returning the Van</h3>\r\nAgain, rental policies vary, but most are the same as standard rental car policies. The gas tank must be filled to the level at pick-up or delivery. Easy enough to accomplish when you stop at a gas station with a car wash (see Cleaning Fee below)—otherwise expect to pay for the refill plus a possible service fee. Also, check for late charges that may apply if the van isn’t returned by the agreed-upon time.\r\n<h3>Cleaning Fee</h3>\r\nA cleaning fee (in the range of $100) may or may not be charged upon your return, depending on whether the van needs more than a routine cleaning (exterior wash, dusting, vacuuming). You might want stop by a car wash in the rental vehicle before you return it to clean it out, make it look as good as the day you began your journey, and avoid a cleaning fee.\r\n<h3>Smoking</h3>\r\nAs a rule, smoking is not permitted in rented handicap vans, and the companies have the ability to detect the odor of cigarette or cigar smoke. You will be charged, so violating the rule is ill-advised.\r\n<h3>Multiple Drivers</h3>\r\nTypically, multiple drivers are permitted as long as they’re listed on the rental contract, have a valid driver’s license, and are covered under a primary renter’s insurance policy.\r\n<h3>Necessary Papers</h3>\r\nBefore you hit the road for parts known and unknown, double-check all the paperwork you have onboard (contract, essential phone numbers, vehicle handbook, etc.), so you’re 100% adventure-ready!\r\n<h3>Where Can I Go?</h3>\r\nYou can’t go to the moon or overseas, and you typically can’t take a rental van out of the US, but all other destinations are awaiting your arrival. It’s time to ramp up your vacation plans!\r\n<h2>About the author</h2>\r\nSusan Hawkins is a writer for AMSVans.com, which rents and sells wheelchair vans and all types of adapted vehicles nationwide with a guaranteed low price on all newly converted AMS-brand wheelchair van models. We sell and convert wheelchair-accessible vans at prices often thousands of dollars lower than the competition. AMSvans.com also accepts trades buys used wheelchair vans at competitive prices. Find adaptive mobility equipment solutions as well as more than 150 handicap vans for sale online at <a href=\"http://www.amsvans.com\" target=\"_blank\">http://www.amsvans.com</a>.", "Guest Journal: “How To Rent a Wheelchair Van for Your Next Vacation” by Susan Hawkins of AMS Vans", "", "inherit", "open", "open", "", "127-revision-v1", "", "", "2013-12-22 14:29:24", "2013-12-22 14:29:24", "", "127", "http://abilitytripwp/127-revision-v1/", "0", "revision", "", "0");
